Jaipur’s last green space is about to be destroyed. 🌳
Dhol Ka Baadh – a forest that houses over 2500 trees, including Rajasthan’s state tree Khejri, more than 50 medicinal plants, and 60+ species of birds – is being cut down to build a mall and a fintech park.

This isn’t just a patch of trees.
It’s the lungs of Jaipur.
A living ecosystem that protects the city from air pollution, water crisis, and rising temperatures.

And yet, in the name of “development,” it’s being erased.

Is development only about concrete and malls?
What about clean air, water, and our right to nature?

🌿 Saving this forest means saving Jaipur’s future.
It’s time to speak up.
#himanshubhatt 
#jaipur #jaipurcity #forest #globalwarming #savedolkabadh

In the past 60 years, we humans have killed over 400 crore tons of marine life, and extracted more than 43 crore tons of carbon, 11 crore tons of nitrogen, and 2.3 crore tons of phosphorus from the oceans. As a result, 56 crore tons of vital nutrients have disappeared from the sea. These nutrients are as essential for the ocean as oxygen is for us.

But when fish populations decline, the natural nutrient cycle of ocean breaks down — or rather, we are the ones who have broken that cycle.

We often talk about saving the environment by saving trees, but we forget one important fact — oceans produce more oxygen than trees.

That’s why, just as it is crucial to save trees, it is equally important to protect our oceans. And oceans can only be saved through the preservation of the life they hold — their biodiversity.

“Wrapped in love, served with tradition – presenting Singori, the sweet gem of Uttarakhand! Made with khoya and wrapped in the aromatic maalu leaf, this melt-in-the-mouth delight is not just a dessert, it’s an emotion. Have you ever tasted this pahadi mithai?”

#uttarakhand #garhwal #garhwali #kumauni #pahadi #himanshubhatt

Ever heard of a sweet that looks like chocolate but tastes like pure tradition?”

Let us introduce you to Bal Mithai – the pride of Uttarakhand and a mouthwatering treat for generations!

This iconic sweet was first made in 1865 by Joga Lal Shah in the beautiful hill town of Almora.
Made from roasted khoya (milk solids) and coated with tiny white sugar balls, Bal Mithai isn’t just a dessert – it’s a legacy passed down through time.

What started in a small sweet shop in Almora is now a world-famous delicacy that carries the flavor of the hills in every bite.

If you haven’t tried Bal Mithai yet… you’re missing a piece of Himalayan heritage!
